# Gut Checc — Research Protocol

Most findings use the Knowledge Base (gut-checc-knowledge.mdc). This protocol is for when the project touches external stuff that needs live verification.

## When to Research

**Go external when:**
- Project uses a specific third-party API (verify endpoints, auth, rate limits)
- A package or library is referenced where version or current syntax matters
- An Anthropic feature is used that might have changed recently (MCP, tool use, new capabilities)
- Project integrates with a platform (Notion, Slack, Sheets, Zapier, etc.)
- You're genuinely unsure if something still works the way you think it does

**Skip research when:**
- The finding is about structure, examples, constraints, or edge cases (Knowledge Base covers this)
- The project is self-contained with no external dependencies
- The principle behind the finding is universal and well-established

## Where to Look

### Tier 1: Anthropic Official
- docs.anthropic.com — main docs
- docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering/overview — prompt engineering hub
- docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering/multishot-prompting — examples and few-shot
- docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering/claude-4-best-practices — latest best practices
- docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code — Claude Code specific
- docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/best-practices — CC patterns, context management, CLAUDE.md structure
- docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/tool-use — MCP and tools
- docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/agents-and-tools/agent-skills/quickstart — Skills API and usage
- docs.anthropic.com/en/api — API reference
- docs.anthropic.com/en/release-notes/claude-code — Claude Code changelog, new features, deprecations
- support.anthropic.com — help center
- support.claude.com/en/articles/12512198-how-to-create-custom-skills — official Skill creation guide
- community.anthropic.com — forums, known issues
- github.com/anthropics/skills — official Skill examples (docx, pdf, pptx, xlsx, algorithmic-art, etc.)
- github.com/anthropics/claude-code/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md — detailed CC changelog for verifying features
- platform.claude.com/docs/en/agents-and-tools/agent-skills/best-practices — official Skill authoring best practices
- code.claude.com/docs/en/skills — Skills documentation, frontmatter reference, progressive disclosure

### Tier 1.5: Community Reference (High Quality)
- github.com/shanraisshan/claude-code-best-practice — community best practice repo (8k+ stars), covers commands, agents, Skills, hooks, CLAUDE.md patterns, orchestration workflows, context management. Useful for CC project evaluation and Learn Why sections.

### Tier 2: Third-Party Official
- Official API docs for the specific tool (not blog posts)
- GitHub repos for open source packages (check issues)
- Changelog or release notes for breaking changes
- agentskills.io — the cross-platform Agent Skills standard. When a Skill uses Claude-only patterns that won't work in Cursor, Codex, or Gemini CLI, this is where to check compatibility

### Tier 3: Community (use carefully)
- High-star GitHub repos using similar approaches
- Stack Overflow for specific patterns
- Only when Tier 1 and 2 don't cover it

## Search Patterns
- `[tool name] + [specific feature] + "documentation"`
- `[tool name] + "breaking changes" + [current year]`
- `[package name] + "known issues"`
- `[Anthropic feature] + "best practices"`

## How Research Shows Up

Research goes into Learn Why sections. Translate it to plain language. Never dump raw docs at the builder.

**Good:** "The Notion API requires an integration token for auth. Right now there's no auth setup here."
**Bad:** Pasting three paragraphs from the Notion docs.

## Speed Rules

- Front-load all research before writing findings. Don't research one finding at a time.
- Don't re-research within a session. If you already checked a source, reuse what you found.
- If research returns nothing useful, say so. "Worth checking [URL] yourself."
- If a finding stands without external verification, skip the lookup.

## The Standard

If a builder asks "how do you know that?" you should be able to point to a source. If you can't, the finding isn't ready.
